sentences: Vivian Alferetta Dandridge (April 22, 1921 – October 26, 1991) was an American singer, actress and dancer.
Dandridge was a member of the Dandridge Sisters musical group, along with Etta Jones and Dorothy Dandridge from 1934 until the group disbanded in 1940.

Dandridge went on to appear in minor roles on films and television from 1940 through the early 1960s.

Never really achieving notable success as her younger sister, Dandridge disappeared from the public eye by 1970.
Dandridge died after suffering a stroke on October 26, 1991 at age 70.
Under Neva's tutelage, the Wonder Children earned $400–$500 per appearance during the late 1920s, touring through Tennessee, South Carolina, Georgia and many other states.
After the stock market crash in 1929, the Wonder Children were added to the long list of the unemployed.
They even appeared in a short-run Broadway musical revue, Swingin' The Dream, in 1939, at the Center Theater.

sentences: After touring for a year and a half, however, the Dandridge Sisters group abruptly disbanded, after  Dorothy was determined to become an actress, unsatisfied with just appearances in occasional soundies or bit parts in Hollywood films.

sentences: Dandridge appeared in some minor film roles: she co-starred with Frances Dee as native girl Melisse in the 1943 classic I Walked with a Zombie and appeared alongside her sister in 1953's Bright Road, where she played a small role of schoolteacher Ms. Nelson (she was uncredited in both films) and acted as Dorothy's hairdresser on the film.
